  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Baseline study of apiculture sector in Kenya</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The demand for honey in Kenya is growing rapidly, yet Kenyan production currently only meets about 50% of the demand. Forest communities across Kenya find their traditional livelihoods threatened by the impact of climate change and extreme weather variability. Apiculture, or bee-keeping, is able to contribute to improved food security, increases in household income and conservation of biological diversity. This project will be undertaken in five districts of Kenya across three zones. Using a range of research techniques, the African Conservation Foundation will seek to understand current practices in production, community organisation and market links. They will assess the current natural resources and environmental status of the communities and identify approaches which most benefit honey and forest communities. As a result, local organisations will be able to support communities to move from bee-keeping to bee-farming, realising increases in income of up to 50%, while conserving forest ecosystems.</narrative>
  </description>
